(1)
Eighteenth Ave., east side, at the N.E. corner of 83rd Street ; showing the New Utrecht Dutch Reformed Church, built in 1828, on site of the old New Utrecht schoolhouse, dedicated in 1829. The church was organized in 1677 in the schoolhouse. The services were held in private dwellinge. A Church was erected in the Dutch burying ground, in 1700, at what is now the N.E. corner of Sixteenth Ave., and 84th
Street. A local minister was installed in 1809.
February 1923.

name: Brooklyn: 18th Avenue - 84th Street

Eighteenth Ave., west side, between 85th and 84th Streets. At the left, is seen the West End line of the B.M.T., on New Utrecht Ave. At the right, is the dunther Railway line and private right of way. It was built in 1863, by C. Godfrey Gunther Fur merchant and Miyor of the City of New York. It ran from 25th Street and Fifth Ave., (Brooklyn), to Coney Tsland. It was also known as the Brooklyn Bath and Coney Island R.R. It is now operated by a trolley Company. At the left, in the triangle, once stood the foundry of Michael Feigel, builder of street and railroad
Cars.

name: Brooklyn: 55th Street (East) - Beverly Road
$.data.text:
East 55th Street, east side, between Beverly and Clarendon Roads, showing District School No. 2, also known as Flatlands Neck School. This structure was built in 1835 or 1837, to replace a smaller school house built in 1786. The older building had originally been standing a little further back, and was moved to the new site given by a member of the Lott Family, who needed the old site for building purposes. The building was razed in 1926, because the site was required for the widening of Kings Highway which cuts diagonally across East 55th Street at this
point.
March 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
(2)
The same, from another angle.
March 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

During the Revolution it became the William Barrie Tavern, at which George Washington is said to have stopped in 1790. Judge John Lott Nostrand was born here in 1856 and lived here until 1902. It was demolished in 1914, to make way for the widening of 84th Street.
About 1900.

name: Brooklyn: Atlantic Avenue - Clinton Street
$.data.text: Atlantic Ave., at the N.E. corner of Clinton Street showing the Brooklyn Athenaeum designed by William Field and erected at a cost of $60,000. The first floor was for commercial enterprises; the second for reading and for private rooms, the third floor had a concert hall capable of seating 2000 people. It gave the first Italian Opera in 1858. The Philharmonic Society held its first concert here. The Reading Room was opened to the public on May 7, 1858. The Mercantile Library was here but later moved to Montague Street. John Homsey purchased it in 1922. In 1929 it housed the Court of Special Sessions.\n1922.\nEugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Atlantic Avenue & Clinton Street, Brooklyn, NY

$.data.text:
Atlantic Ave., east from a point east of the intersection of East New York and Atlantic Aves., showing at the left, the Central Hotel which later housed the Brooklyn Daily Eagle. At the right background, is a turreted building, which was Jewell's 26th Ward Bank; established in 1888, by Ditmas Jewell at No. 2500 Atlantic Ave., in rented quarters, on March 25, 1889. The first location was at the corner of Georgia Ave. The cornerstone for the new building was laid on July 7, 1891, and the building opened March 3, 1892.

1897.

name: Brooklyn: Bedford Avenue - Lafayette Avenue
$.data.text:
1002-1024 Bedford Ave., west side, between Lafayette and De Kalb Aves.(No. 1024, is at the left foreground). A view of the First German Lutheran Church, known as St. Peter's German Evang. Lutheran Church, which was organized on November 17, 1867.

June 1923.

The fiftieth anniversary of the dedicating of the edifice of St. Peter's Lutheran Church was celebrated yesterday morning by the congregation. The sermon was by the Rev. Dr. Ellis B. Burgess, president of the United Lutheran Synod of New York. The Rev. Dr. J. G. F. Blaesi, pastor, officiated at the altar, wearing a silk robe and clerical vest given him in honor of his forty years as a clergman, which he will complete in July, according to the New York Times of May 23, 1938.

name: Brooklyn: Bradford Street - Fulton Street
$.data.text:
109 Bradford Street, east side, between Fulton Street and Atlantic Ave., showing the New Lots Town Hall. In 1937 it is the Bradford Street Hospital. The plot (100 x 50 feet), was purchased from Horace A. Miller for $1400 and the Town Hall was opened on December 11, 1873. The police station occupied the ground floor; the basement was used as a prison. After 1886 it served solely as a station house. On November 13, 1899 the present hospital was opened as the 26th Ward Homeopathic Hospital and Dispensary.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Bradford Street & Fulton Street, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Bradford Street - Atlantic Avenue
$.data.text:
Bradford Street, (formerly Butler Street), west side, south of Atlantic Ave., showing the Turn Hall, a frame structure 57 1/2' x 60', erected at a cost of $4,000. It was formally opened on July 4, 1864. The small house next to the Hall was a school in 1873, but was subsequently converted into a
court house.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Brighton Beach Avenue - 4th Street (East)
$.data.text:
(1)
Brighton Beach Ave., south side, East 4th Street and Coney Island Ave. showing the Brighton Beach Hotel, which was built by the Brighton Beach Co., in 1878, and opened for business the same year. The work was started on March 20, 1878. When this hotel was first erected it was 600 feet from high water, but in 1888 the Atlantic had undermined the foundations necessitating the placing of the hotel upon piles. However on April 3, 1888 it was moved inland 500 feet by B.C. Miller and 5 Sons who contracted the work. The hotel was razed in 1924. The owners or lessees of this hotel were Breslin and Sweet 1879, Leland 1883, Cunningham and Hatfield 1888, and E. Clark King 1902-1909.
December 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, viewed eastward.
December 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(3)
The same, a front view.
December 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(4)
The same, showing a side view of the hotel, the hand-ball court, the grand-stand and the merry-go-round.
December 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Brighton Beach Avenue & 4th Street (East), Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Broadway - Halsey Street
$.data.text:
Broadway, east side, south from Halsey Street. (In 1871 Paul W. Ledoux, a Canadian who resided in New York City, bought a lot of land bounded by Broadway, Bushwick Ave., and Eldert and Halsey Streets, on which 13 stores and several dwellings were erected. In 1891, he refused $100,000 for a 200 feet frontage on Broadway. In 1905 he sold 180' X 1O0' on Broadway for $225,000. He, among others, was instrumental in having the Halsey Street trolley line extended). Overhead is a portion of the
Broadway line of the Brooklyn Elevated system.
July 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Clarendon Road - 59th Street (East)
$.data.text:
(1) Clarendon Road, south side, (formerly known as Canarsie Lane, at this point), between East 59th Street and Ralph Ave., showing the S.W. view of the Pieter Claesen Wyckoff Farmhouse, built in 1664. The south side of the house is covered with the original shingles. In 1890 the original roof was replaced by a tin roof. This house was originally occupied by Pieter Claesen Wyckoff and subsequently by his son Claes, followed by Claes' son Peter in 1719. In 1860 it was occupied by John A. Wyckoff; in 1873 by John W. Wyckoff and in 1901, the heirs of John A. Wyckoff sold it to Francis Gross.

March 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, in 1923.

1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Clarendon Road & 59th Street (East), Brooklyn, NY

Clarendon Road, north side, (formerly called Canarsie Lane at this point), between East 59th Street and Ralph Ave., showing the north side of the Albert Terhune Lott House, nearly opposite the Wyckoff House. The house was occupied by John Lott in 1794, by Albert Terhune Lott, between 1860 and 1873, and sold and vacated by the Lott family about 1903. In an upper room were found the Terhune family papers. This
house is no longer in existence.
About 1923.

name: Brooklyn: Clinton Street - Montague Street
$.data.text:
(1)
Clinton Street, at the N. W. corner of Montague Street, showing the Holy Trinity Protestant Episcopal Church. The foundation for this edifice,of which Edgar John Barton was the builder, was begun in August 1844. The chapel opened for services on June 7, 1846, and the church on April 25, 1847. The steeple, which was erected in 1860, was removed in 1906. Two buildings (not in this view) at Nos. 122-124 Pierrepont Street were given to the parish by George Foster Peabody in 1905 and 1912, to be used as a guilderhouse and parish house. The rectory was purchased in 1897, and is at No. 126 Pierrepont Street. The church proper oost t175,000; the spire 275 feet in height, cost an additional
965,000. Minard Lefevre was the architect.
About 1906
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The Montague Street side of the church, viewing eastward. The 3y story building on the extreme left is the Trinity
Club.
March 1, 1929
P. L. Sperr
(3)
Another view of the church, vlewing northwestward across the roof of the Brooklyn Trust Company bu'lding (right foreground).
March 1, 1929
P. L. Sperr
$.data.folder: Clinton Street & Montague Street, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Cortelyou Road - Canarsie Avenue
$.data.text:
Cortelyou Road, (Canarsie Lane), at the N.E. corner of Canarsie Ave. (01d Clove Road), showing Guard house of the Holy Cross Cemetery. This cemetery, named Galilee, was also referred to as the "Cemetery of the Catholic's". Bishop John H. Hughes aoquired in June 1849, 17 acres of land from James Duffey. This land was once a section ot the Van Brunt farm. In 1857, another 19 acres were purchased from the heirs of Adrian Vanderveer. In 1869, another 22 acres were purchased from Lefferts Cornell. The first body interred, July 14, 1849, was that of Thomas Moran, the first victim
of the cholera in Flatbush.
May 12, 1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Court Street - Montague Street
$.data.text:
A general view west from the Temple Bar Building located at the S.W. corner of Court and Montague Streets, showing the Brooklyn Heights section of Brooklyn between Remsen Street (extreme left) and Fulton Street (extreme rights). In the foreground is the Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity at the N.W. corner of Montague and Clinton Streets. At the left background is the Hotel Bossert at the S.E. corner of Montague and Hicks Streets. Also shown is the Manhattan skyline and at the right a part of the Brooklyn Bridge. Note the junction of the East and North Rivers with Upper New York Bay. The New Jersey skyline vaguely appears in the left background.

1926.
Brown Brothers.
Neg. #5027
$.data.folder: Court Street & Montague Street, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Court Street - Montague Street
$.data.text:
Court Street, west side, from Montague (right) to Remsen Streets. On the extreme right is the Mechanics Bank Building at the northwest corner of Court and Montague Streets. To the left of it, at the S.W. corner of the two streets, is the Continental Insurance Building (narrow buildfng) and the Phoenix Tnsurance Building. These two were torn down in 1926 and the 35-story Montague-Court Building erected on the site. The clearance to the left of the Phoenix Building, which is the northwest corner of Court and Remsen Streets, is the former site of the Garfield Building, where the 29-story Court-Remsen Building was later put up. The view is across Borough Hall Park from Fulton Street. The statue (center left) is that of Henry Ward Beecher, d'stinguished preacher of the Plymouth Church and
abolitionist.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection 1925

Court Street, east side, south from Joralemon to Livingston Streets. In the foreground is the Washington Building, erected about 1851 and torn down in 1924, behind which is a small municipal park. The building with the sloping roof is the Brooklyn Polytechnic Institute on Livingston Street. The Washington Building and the three buildings contiguous to it were later torn down and the Municipal Building erected on the site. The other structures are still standing in 1929.

name: Brooklyn: Cranberry Street - Henry Street
$.data.text:
Cranberry Street, south side, between Henry and Hicks Streets, viewing west from near Henry Street and showing the Plymouth Church, from which the famous Brooklvn preacher Henry Ward eecher delivered his sermons. The church was built in 1849 and extends through to Orange Street. The three-story house with the brownstone stoop, to the left of the church, is Henry Ward Beecher's old home and President Abraham Lincoln and General Ulysses S. Grant are ssid to have visited here. The house is No. 66 Cranberry Street and was remodelled, in 1940, into an apartment hose for five families. For additional
data see "The New York Times," October 5, 1940.
View 1: Eugene L. Armbruster Collection 1922
View 2: P. L. Sperr

Cranberry Street, south side, between Henry and Hicks Streets, showing the old Plymouth Church, built in 1849 and made famous by its preacher Henry Ward Beecher. A brass plate in the church marks the pew where Abraham Lincoln, a personal friend of the minister, sat to hear his sermons. The first three-story brownstone house, to the left of the church, is Henry Ward Beecher's old home, No. 66 Cranberry Street, and the Civil War President and General 'lysses S. Erant are said to have visited here. In 1940 the house was transformed into a five-family apartment house.

name: Brooklyn: Devoe Street - Lorimer Street
$.data.text: 36-42 Devoe Street, south side, just west of Lorimer Street, showing the J . A. Rhodes' saw factory. It was built on 1850. This is the rear of the factory. Although Mr. Armbruster states that the factory was located on Ainslie Street near Tenth Street, the present (1941) Keap Street, the writer of these lines was unable to locate any saw factory at that location from 1874 to the present. The only saw factory, or file factory (the two are used interchangeably in the old Brooklyn business directories), in this area appears in Bromley's 1880 map on the south side of Devoe Street (which is one block north of Ainslie Street), just west of Lorimer Street. It is very likely that this is the saw factory Mr. Armbruster has in mind.\nEugene L. Armbruster Collection about 1890\n

name: Brooklyn: New York Avenue (East) - Williams Avenue
$.data.text:
(1)
East New York Ave., north side, opposite Williams Ave., showing the home of James L. Williams. This house, dating from 1843, has been also known as Tubbs Hotel. It originally faced the intersection of the Brooklyn and eamaica Plank Road (Fulton Street) and Flatbush Road (East New York Ave). New (1922) the house faces East New York Ave., having been turned and moved about 100 feet westward. On the Kirng's County Map of 1873 in the Atlas of Long Island, the Williams estate owned lots 21 to 59 in the area. The Trinity Hospital owns most of
this property, and occupies this house (in 1937).
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, showing house No. 1829, to the left ef the hospital.
April 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(also known as the Brooklyn Museum).
About 1925.
Ewing Galloway.
$.data.folder: Eastern Parkway & Washington Avenue, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Eastern Parkway - Franklin Avenue
$.data.text:
Eastern Parkway north of Franklin Ave.
A general view west and northwest of Franklin Ave., showing in the background, in Institute Park, the Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences. To the right is Eastern Parkway. Franklin Ave., is visible in the foreground. Washington Ave., is east and south in front of the Arts building; also is Classon Ave., and the Manhattan Beach and Coney Island branch of the Long Island R.R. Union and President Streets, now run east and west to the left of Eastern Parkway to Institute Park. In the foreground west of Franklin Ave., now stands the Girls Commercial High School, east of Franklin Ave., on property of 1. & S. Smith, large apartment houses have been built. All buildings east of the Arts building and east of Eastern Parkway, have been demolished. The cornerstone for the Institute was laid in 1896 by Mayor Charles A. Schieren. The two sections of this building were completed in 1897 and 1904. The apprentices Library Association and the Old Brooklyn Institute founded in 1823 and 1843 respectively, were incorporated, in 1890, into this organization. The former building of the old institute was practically
destroyed by fire on September 12, 1890.
About 1910.
$.data.folder: Eastern Parkway & Franklin Avenue, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Eastern Parkway - Utica Avenue
$.data.text:
Eastern Parkway at the N.W. corner of Utica Avenue,
showing the East New York Savings Bank.

The crowd in front of the bank is worried about their savings. The reason the bank is closed is because of President Franklin D. Roosevelt's order closing all banks in the early part of 1933. The bank could not be reopened until declared solvent by the Federal and State Bank Examiners.

About 1933

P. A. View 4 is in a westerly direction and shows, in the background, the Bayview Apartments.

name: Brooklyn: Flatbush Avenue - Eastern Parkway
$.data.text:
Flatbush Ave. (right) south of Eastern Parkway, showing prominently the $1,000,000 political football, that was to have been the Central Library of Brooklyn, but it was never completed. To the left, partially seen, is the domed structure, known as the Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences. The elevated land to the left of the Library is the Mt. Prospect Reservoir. View No. 2 shows the $1,000,000 scandal being demolished for the erection of a new library.
January 1, 1937.
View 2: June 12, 1938.
P. L. Sperr.

name: Brooklyn: Flatbush Avenue - Maple Street
$.data.text:
(1)
563 Flatbush Ave., east side, betneen Maple and Midwood Streets. This house clearly marked on the map of 1908 of Brooklyn. The view is the Lefferts Farmhouse, removed in 1918, to Prospect Park. It stood at 563 Flatbush Ave., upon which site is now the North Cliff Hall Apartments. It was built by Pieter Lefferts (1753-1791), on site of an earlier house (built 1666), destroyed in the Battle of Flatbush, during
the Revolution.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
This is a post out of the Lefferts barn 112 years old, stood on the Canarsie Lane near Midwood Street. It was razed in 1904. It was built in 1792. 373-375 Midwood Street, occupy the site.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Flatbush Avenue & Maple Street, Brooklyn, NY

1325 Flushing Ave., north side, east of Cypress Ave., showing in the foreground, the Nicholas Wyckoff farmhouse, accuired in 1765; from a Schenck. Another Nicholas Wyckoff was owner from 1852-1860. For more

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, looking south, showing a rear view of the out-buildings
of the farmhouse.

(3)
The same, showing another angle. Note that one of the barns is
partially demolished by fire.

(4)
The same, showing another close up of the barn. It was erected in 1650 or 1656 (marked on rafter) and partially demolished by fire in 1700. The original joists remained and the barn was rebuilt around them.
It was again partially destroyed by fire in March 1922.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

data see the N.Y. Sun. February 18, 19 1666.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, looking south, showing a rear view of the out-buildings
of the farmhouse.
September 1928.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(3)
The same, showing another angle. Note that one of the barns is
partially demolished by fire.
September 1928.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(4)
The same, showing another close up of the barn. It was erected in 1650 or 1656 (marked on rafter) and partially demolished by fire in 1700. The original joists remained and the barn was rebuilt around them.
It was again partially destroyed by fire in March 1922.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Flushing Avenue - Cypress Avenue
$.data.text:
1325 Flushing Ave., north side, between Cypress Ave., and Seneca Avenue,showing in a set of four views the Nicholas Wyckoff house, also known as the Peter Wyckoff home. Views 1 and 2 are the same. No. 3 is a rear view, looking southwest towards Flushing Ave. No. 4 is a partial view of No. 2. Peter Wyckoff occupied this house during the Revolutionary War. Prior to this, in 1765, it was the Schenck farmhouse. In that year Nicholas Ayckoff acquired possession. Eugene L. Armbruster states that a broad hall runs through the center of the house, on the left side of the hall is a parlor and sitting room. On the other side of the hall is a dining room, kitchen, and three bedrooms. In the sitting room is a colonial mantle piece, having pictures of the old Rapelye, Johnson, and Wyckoff houses. The upper floors contain eight rooms and a garret. In a corner of the hall is an ancient grandfather clock still keeping time. See other 09. views for more data. For ore data see the N.Y. Sun, February 18,
September 1928.
Views 1 & 4.
Views 2 & 3: 1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Fort Hamilton Parkway - 99th Street
$.data.text:
(1)
Fort Hamilton Parkway, at the N.W. corner of 99th Street, showing St. John's Episcopal Church and a double frame house (Nos. 9808-9810). The church was organized in this community in the farmhouse of one Denyse, at the N.E. corner of Fort Hamilton Parkway and 101st Street, on September 29, 1834. The Denyse heirs reserved a 1ot (100' x 125') the present site, on which a frame building was erected. It was consecrated on July 16, 1835. On Dec. 24, 1890 this building was partly burned, resulting in its demolition and the erecting of the present one in 1897, which was consecrated on danuary 5, 1898.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, showing the chapel belonging to the church which is part1y seen at the extreme left in No. 1.

Fulton Street, between Hicks and Water Streets, showing different phases of W.P.A. highway and sewer operations. View 4 shows part of the Brooklyn Bridge and the skeleton of a new storehouse for the Department of Purchase. In the background is the Manhattan Bridge.

1936
Views 1, 2, 3, 4

Works Project Administration
Five Boroughs Project
$.data.folder: Fulton Street & Hicks Street, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Fulton Street - Furman Street
$.data.text:
Fulton Street, at the N.W. corner of Furman Street. A view of the Brooklyn City Flour Mills, owned by Jewell Brothers, who organized the Jewell Milling Company in 1880. (This site no longer serves as a mill in 1908). On the opposite corner (S.W.), was a railroad terminus for passengers from and to New York. The Brooklyn Bridge
was still under construction.

About 1880 ?

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
$.data.folder: Fulton Street & Furman Street, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Fulton Street - Elizabeth Place
$.data.text:
26 Fulton Street, at the S.W. corner of Elizabeth Place, showing the building in which Hans Bergen carried on a bakery from 1717 to about 1730, in conjunction with a store, and a stable for horses of the residents of the Island when crossing to New York. The stable was a stone building, located, as near as can be ascertained, on the westerly corner of Fulton and Elizabeth Streets. A portion of the walls of which are supposed to form the easterly end of the building located there. In 1840, it was N. Guerneys' Mechanic 's 1
Hotel.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Fulton Street & Elizabeth Place, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Fulton Street - Hicks Street
$.data.text:
47 Fulton Street, north side, at the head of Hicks Street, showing the old Long Island Bank, established in 1824. The bank occupied this building fromm 1876 to 1880. In 1892 the bank was at 186 Remsen Strret. A broom selling concern later took over the builditg. Two signs at the entrance to the building read: "Spriral Tube Brushes"
and "Rattan-Bass Push Brooms."
1923
Views 1,2
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
(3)
Another view of the old bank building.
February 5, 1931
P. L. Sperr

name: Brooklyn: Fulton Street - Joralemon Street
$.data.text:
Fulton Street, east from Joralemon Street. At the right, on Joralemon Street, are the King's County Court House and the Hall of Record, followed by the King's County Trust Co. At the left, the Citizen Building houses the "Brooklyn Daily Citizen". The Boerum Place station of the Fulto
Street elevated lines may also be seen.
About 1900.
$.data.folder: Fulton Street & Joralemon Street, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Fulton Street - Joralemon Street
$.data.text:
Fulton Street (elevated structure thereon), south side, east from its intersection with Joralemon Street, showing a general view southeastward as seen from the Temple Bar Building which is located on the west side of Court Street (No. 44) at the N.W. corner of Joralemon Street. At the right of the Fulton Street Elevated line, beginning with the foreground, are in their order, the following buildings; namely, the new and old Munteipal Buildings, and the Hall of Records. The triangular roofed building to the left is at the intersection of Wtlloughby and Fulton Streets. The
elevated station is on Boerum Place.
May 1926.
Brown Brothers.

name: Brooklyn: Fulton Street - Crescent Street
$.data.text:
Fulton Street, at the N.E. corner of Crescent Street. The corner building which faces both Fulton and Crescent Streets, are Nos. 3345-3351 and 229-233 respectively. The Fulton Street Elevated structure turns into Crescent Street, at this point. This building once known as the Lafayette Hotel (saloon) was operated by a Captain Hy. Koerner and later his widow, from 1872-1902. It was later known as Starks Old Roadhouse when it was damaged by fire on February 18, 1922.

name: Brooklyn: Hanson Place - Ashland Place
$.data.text:
Hanson Place, at the N.E. corner of Ashland Place, showing the towered structure of the Williamsburg Bank. The small buildings to the left of same (east side of Ashland Place) are the Salvation Army Quarters. Continuing to the left (north of the latter) is the Academy of Music Building. The vacant lot shown at the N.W. corner of Hanson Place and St. Felix Street was the site of the former Hanson Place M.E. Church. On the extreme lower right appears the low structure of the Long Island Rail-road Station, one side of which is on Flatbush Ave., which has the Fifth Ave. Elevated Line thereon. In the background, intersecting Lafayette
Ave., is Fulton Street and its Elevated Line.
About 1929.
Ewing Galloway.

name: Brooklyn: Highland Park.

name: Brooklyn: Irving Avenue - Putman Avenue
$.data.text:
Union Cemetery, Brooklyn:
Northwestward across the Fethodist Cemetery on whose site was erected, years later, the Bushwick High School. The fence runs along the west side of Irving Avenue, from Putnam Avenue to Palmetto Street. The entire cemetery grounds, with the exception of the extreme right corner, later became the Bushwick High School and playgrounds.
Eugene L. Armbruster collection. About 1827

name: Brooklyn: Lott Place - Flatbush Avenue
$.data.text:
Lott Place, at the S.E. corner of Flatbush Ave. and Kings Highway, showing the Reg Hegeman Farmhouse, which was later named the Van Wyck House. This house was reputed to date from 1780; others, however, claim it was built much earlier in the century. It was demolished in 1910. The property was owned by C. Stevens, but in 1722 Jan Lucasse and Johanus Voorhees sold it to one Hogelands; Rem Hegeman bought it of a Van Dyke in 1795 and another Van Dyke bought it of H. Hogelands in 1825. This property was in the Van Wyck family and heirs until 1916.
1908.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Meeker Avenue - Gardner Avenue
$.data.text:
(1)
Meeker Ave., south side, between Gardiner Ave., and Newtown Creek, alleged to have been built by Humphrey Clay in 1667, it stood until 1921 when it was demolished about 50 or 60 ft. from Newtown Creek. The owners of this property are as follows:- patented in 1646 by Adan Mott who sold to William Geulding; who sold to Clandine Baybine and Anthony Jerve of Newgate Kills; who sold to Jacob Steendam in 1653. It was again patented by Humphrey Clay in 1667. He operated a ferry here as late as 1670. His son Clay sold to Alexander Baird of Hempstead, who left it to his wife Magdaleun. The first recorded sale is in 1749, from Josiah Paterson to Joost Dorre, who by will in 1793 left his real estate of Bushwick and Newtown to his sons, George and Peter. The former conveyed to Peter in 1795, the latters will convey in 1828 part to Anthony Hulst and the rest including the house to John Reis. From 1880 to 1924 William Blesser, and his heirs were owners.
1920.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, another view.
About 1920.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Meeker Avenue & Gardner Avenue, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Monroe Place - Clark Street
$.data.text:
Monroe Place, at the S.E. corner of Clark Street, showing The Church Of The New Jerusalem purchased in 1868, by the Brooklyn Society of The New Church (Swedenborgian), which was organized on June 15, 1859, from the congres gation of The Church Of Our Father, a Universalist Society, founded in October 1842, who held their first services in a hall at the corner of Fulton and Cranberry Streets. The society later erected a new building at the corner of Pineapple and Fulton Streets. Iu 1848, the latter building was destroyed by fire, and the structure in this view was erected; and named "The Church Of Our Father". The congregation of this church with that of "The Church Of The Redeemer"- a group4dissenters- again combined in 1868 and moved to the
corner of Grand Ave., and Leffert's Place in 1883.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

35-41 Montague Street, north side, just east of Henry street, showing three brownstone houses, Nos. 39 to 41. No. 35 is the fenced-off empty lot on the left which is up for sale by the D.&M. Chauncey Beal Estate Company. A two-story brick building was later erected here and was occupied by Fendleton and Fendleton. The first house, No. 37, was used as a branch by the American Bible Society.

View 3 shows the lot at No. 35, and the house occupied by the Bible Society (No. 37). Also shown are the rears of three dwellings which front on the south side of Pierpont Street and are No. 98, 96, and 90 (left). No. 96, the center house is the Turner house.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection About 1916

name: Brooklyn: Myrtle Avenue - Palmetto Street
$.data.text:
(1)
At the intersection of Myrtle Ave., with Palmetto Street and Wyckoff Ave., showing (center) at the N.E. corner of Myrtle Ave., and Palmetto Street. The 4-story building owned by the Bushwick R.R. Co., had its offices and stables, on land owned by Peter Meserole in 1855. This building was partly destroyed by fire on September 15, 1923. The cafe at the right, is at the S.E. corner of Wyckoff and Myrtle Aves. To the left is a portion of the Myrtle Ave. Elevated line of the B.M.T. (The elevated makes a sharp turn from Myrtle Ave., into Palmetto Street at this point).
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, showing a closer view of the R.R. Co's building.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)
The same, showing the opposite corner occupied by the Parthenon Theatre. The theatre's site was originally part of the Ganta Farm, which was sold for $4,000 per acre, to the Bushwick R.R. Co., which erected its Ridgewood Depot and stables here in 1872. This corner while in Brooklyn in 1916, is now (1929) in Queens County.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4)
The same, showing the R.R. Co's building after the fire.
1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Orange Street - Henry Street
$.data.text:
Orange Street, north side, between Henry and Hicks Streets, showing the Plymouth Church, from which the well-known Brooklyn preacher Henry Ward Beecher delivered his sermons. The church was built in 1849 and a brass plate on one of the pews indicates where Abrsham Lincoln, friend of the minister, sat to henr his sermons. The edifice extends through to Cranberry Street, one block to the north, and views of that side of the building can be found in the Cranberry Street file. The views (except 3) are east from Hicks
Street.
For additional data see "The New York Times," October 5, 1940.
Views 1,2,3: 1925
Eugene L. Armbruster
View 4: June 11, 1927
P. L. Sperr

name: Brooklyn: Orange Street - Hicks Street

Orange Street, north side, between Hicks and Henry Streets, showing the old Plymouth Church, built in 1849, from which Henry Ward Beecher, Brooklyn's famous preacher, delivered his sermons. Abraham Lincoln, who was a personal friend of the minister, came here to hear his sermons. Walter Damrosch,noted composer and orchestra conductor, at one time served here as musical director under Beecher. View 1 is east from Hicks Street; view 2, west from Henry Street.

For additional pictures see the Cranberry Street file for views of that side of the church edifice, and for additional data see "The New York Times," October 5, 1940.

April 4, 1932
Views 1,2,3

F.L.Sperr

name: Brooklyn: Oriental Boulevard - Ocean Avenue
$.data.text:
(1) Oriental Boulevard, south side, west of Ocean Ave., showihg the Manhattan Beach Hotel built by Elbert Snediker in 1877 and owned by Austin Corbin, who opened it on July 18, 1877. The 4-story west wing was added in 1876, and it was again enlarged in 1879, Overall, the hotel was 660 feet long and accomodated 500 people. Its owners or lessees were H.3. Breslin, 1883; Simieon Leland, 1891; T.F. Silleck, 1809-1901; Alfred T. Amer, 1909-1910; and Jeseph P. Greaves, 1911,when iwas demolished in the same year. In 1937 the Manhattan Beach Baths used the site as a parking place for automobiles.

September 20, 1911.

The same, showing a close up of the "Church on the Heights" (Reformed). The Congregation of this church organiszed in 1837 and erected their first place of worship on Henry Street as the "Central Church" (Dutch Reformed) in 1839. They disbanded in 1841 and the remainder of the Congregation formed the above named church shortly thereafter and laid the corner
stone at the present location in 1849.
1922.
Mugee Armbruster Collection. MAe BE REPRDUCED.

name: Brooklyn: Pierrepont Street - Monroe Place
$.data.text:
Pierrepont Street, at the N.E. corner of Monroe Place, showing the First Unitarian Church of the Saviour. The first services conducted by this church were held in Classical Hall on Washington Street, August 17, 1833. The first pastor was Rev. David H. Barlow, who served until 1838. In 1835 it purchased and moved into the building formerly occupied by the Second Presbyterian Church on Adams Street, (afterwards known as Gothic Hall). The congregation incorporated and became known as the First Unitarian Church of Brooklyn, after the dedication of the present building on April 24, 1844, the present name was adopted. At the left is 50 Monroe Place, and to the right is 121-123 Pierrepont Street.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Pierrepont Street & Monroe Place, Brooklyn, NY

Prospect Park,Plaza: A general view east from the Knights of Columbus Building located at the N.W. corner of President Street and Prospect Park West, showing in the foreground the Memorial Arch. In the center of the view, east from Flatbush Ave., (trolley car thereon) is Eastern Parkway. The buildings on the south side of the Parkway are the Mt. Prospect Reservoir, and the Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences; on the north side in their order are the Union Temple of Brooklyn, the Copley Plaza Apartments (under construction), the Abraham Lincoln, etc.

June 1926.

Brown Brothers.

name: Brooklyn: Prospect Park - Fair Ground Inc.
$.data.text:
(1)
Prospect Park Fair Grounds Inc., bounded on the north by King's Highway, on the west by Mc Donald Ave., on the south by Neck Road, on the east by Coney Island Ave., was composed of 60 acres purchased by Geo. Powers and J. Payton, who established a one mile trotting course. These grounds were sold to a group of prominent Brooklyn residents, who formed the Brooklyn Jockey Club, which enlarged this tract to 460 acres at a cost of $400,000. It was opened in 1887. This view shows a straightaway and "Grand Stand" - To-day (1929) Stryker Street runs through the front of and along the site of the stand. The new tract was bounded on the north by Ave. Q, on the east by Ocean Parkway, on the west by Mc Donald Ave., and East 2nd Street, and on the south by Ave. V and Johnson Lane. The Dwyer brothers and the prominent Brooklynites incorporated under the name of the Brooklyn Jockey Club Track of Gravesend, Inc. The last meet was held in 1910. In 1922, the grounds were sold for $750,000 to William E. Harriman, and this section became known as the King's Club district.
?
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, after the demolition of track buildings.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Prospect Park & Fair Ground Inc., Brooklyn, NY

Ralph Ave. (man thereon), at the southwest corner of Broadway (elevated structure thereon) showing a three-story frame structure known as Cobly Hall in 1875. Church services were held here from 1875-1877 by the Trinity Baptist Church, and in 1884, by the German Presbyterian Friedess Kirche. It was subsequently known as Ridgewood Hall; Schumacher's Cafe once occupied the ground floor.

June 1923

name: Brooklyn: Remsen Street - Clinton Street
$.data.text:
Remsen Street, west from Clinton Street. In the left foreground is the Hamilton Club, organized on November 2, 1830 as the Young Men's Literary Association; changing its name in October 1831 to the Hamilton Literary Association of Brooklyn. Henry C. Murphy became its first president. Ninety of these members founded the present club which was incorporated in May 1882. The first quarters of the organization were in the Hamilton Building, at the N.W. corner of Court and Joralemon Streets, now the Temple Bar Building. In 1884 its present site was purchased at a cost of e:9,000. The Clubhouse cost another551,000, The statue of Alexander Hamilton was erected in 1892. Also partially seen are the Church of the Pilgrims and
the Hotel Bossert.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Remsen Street & Clinton Street, Brooklyn, NY

(2)
The same, showing the corner. Now (1936) a 23-story building
occupies this site.

Remsen Street, west from, and including Court Street. Also seen is Court Street, from, but not including Montague Street, to, but not including Joralemon Street. On the extreme right, is the Old Phenix Insurance Building, now gone; the new building is 16 Court Street. In the extreme left, is the front of the Brooklyn Municipal building, and the top part of it showing the clock tower still functioning.

May 1926.

Brown Brothers.

name: Brooklyn: St. Edwards Street - Auburn Place
$.data.text:
St. Edwards Street, north from Auburn Place toward the Brooklyn Navy Yard. On the left, where Leo Place meets St. Edwards Street, is the Latte_sen shoe factory. On the right is Public School No. 67. The dwellings preceding the school were later razed and an annex added to the school.

All the buildings on the west side of the street were later razed, as shown in views 2 and 3, to make way for a new public housing construction. The shoe factory can be seen coming down in the later views, view 3 being north on Leo Place and shows also the public school and with its annex.

P. L. Sperr
View 1: October 31, 1937
View 2, 3: April 22, 1941
$.data.folder: St. Edwards Street & Auburn Place, Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Schenck Avenue - 92nd Street (East)
$.data.text:
9217 Schenck Avenue, north side, between East 92nd and East 93rd Streets, viewing toward the latter and showing Bill's O1d Homestead Beer Garden. Here Billy Ray for more than thirty years operated a bar known as the "madhouse," because of electrical gadgets that shocked customers when they picked up their change or sst on certain chairs. The house, which was formerly three stories high, was practically ramed by fire in 1933. It was later demolished to make way for the construction of
the Belt Parkway.
View 2 is across East 92nd Street.
July 6, 1933
Views 1,2

name: Brooklyn: Sheepshead Bay Road - 6th Street (West)
$.data.text:
Sheepshead Bay Road, north side, between West 6th and 8th Streets, showing a rear view. Also seen is the rear of the Oceanic HEotel which was the original Coney Island House. It was built in 1829 and stood on Neptune Ave., opposite Shell Road, south of Coney Island Creek. This property was sold by a road Company to John and Albert TTerhunef later owned by Peter Lott. One Tooker was the first keeper of the house 0thers who either owned or operated the house were James W. Cropsey in 1834; Cropsey and Woglom from 1835-1843; A. Fetter, S.W. Fetter, and John I. Snediker in the 1870s and 1880s. In the Brooklyn Atlas, it is now looated at No. 2866 Wost 6th Street, west side, between Neptune Ave.,
and Sheepshead Bay Road.
December 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
The same, viewed from Sheepshead Bay Road.
Ootober 1928.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Shore Road - 83rd Street
$.data.text:
Shore Road, west side, opposite 83rd Street, showing the Crescent Athletic Club's boat-house, which was destroyed by fire in April 1933. This organization has its origin in a football club, organized in 1884 by William H. Ford, and was on leased grounds located at the corner of 9th Ave and 9th Street, Brooklyn. The club v ich was incorporated in Feb. 1888, took over in the spring of 1889 the land and boat-house of the Nereid Boat Club. In the same year they purchased from the Van Brunt and Bergen estates of Bay Ridge a tract of land extending from 83rd to 85th Streets, and from Shore Road to Colonial Road. On Decoration Day 1892, the club house which cost $80,O00 was opened to the members.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Elliott Place S.) - Hanson Place
$.data.text:
South Elliott Place (left foreground), south of Hanson Place to Atlantic Ave. This view is also general and shows the southern section of Brooklyn. It was taken from atop the Y.M.C.A. Building located at 55 Hanson Place, which is between Fort Greene and South Elliott Places. To the right of South Elliott Place is Fort Greene Place. At the left, beyond the Long Island freight yards on the S.E. and S.W. corners of Sixth Ave. respectively are the Sheffield Farms Co. and the A.G. Spalding Co. Manufacturing buildings. Fifth Ave. is a continuation of Fort Greene Place. The trolley car on Fifth Ave. is crossing Pacific Street to enter Flatbush Ave. At the right beyond the triangle is the Fifth Ave. Elevated Line on Flatbush Ave., which swings sharply and continues southward on Fifth Ave.
June 1926.
Brown Brothers.

name: Brooklyn: Throop Ave. - Hart St.
$.data.text:
(1)
Throop Ave., west side, north from, but not including Hart to Willoughby Streets, showing the Throop Ave. Presbyterian Church, which had its origin in a mission established in 1852, on the corner of Throop Ave., and Bartlett Street. The church as such was organized on June 8, 1862, at Throop Ave., near Hopkins Street. In 1867 it moved to a small frame building at the S.W. corner of Throop and Willoughby Aves. The cornerstone of this building, was laid on November 2, 1889. A part of the wall fell during a storm on January 9, 1890. The edifice was opened for service on November 2, 1890; shortly thereafter it was destroyed by fire. A new site was later acquired at the corner of Throop Ave. and Macon Street.
October 12, 1911.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
$.data.folder: Throop Ave. & Hart St., Brooklyn, NY

name: Brooklyn: Tillary St. - Jay St.
$.data.text:
Tillary Street, west from Jay Street, showing more of the south side of the street. The 6-story white building is the Brooklyn Edison Company Building, at Pearl Street, and beyond that, across the "El," is a corner of the United States Post Office. In the left background is the Montague-Court Building.

View 2: September 9, 1939
P. L. Sperr

View 2 shows the S.E. corner of Tillary and Jay Streets, Tillary being on the left, extending to Lawrence Street; Jay Street is on the right. The cleared area is the same as that seen on the right in view 1, where the buildings were razed.

Ave. U., south side, west of Gerritsen Creek, sho ing a house in the foreground, which is in the line of Burnett Street. At some future date it will be either moved or demolished because of the extensiou of Burnett Street. When the streets are finally cut into this property, the Whitney house which will no longer be in existence would, if standing be in Marine Park Property at the N.E. corner of Ave. V. and Burnett
Street, and the barn would be on the S.W. oorner.
August 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

The same, another view.

September 1928.

February 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, view eastward.
February 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)
The same, a view north from the Old Gravesend Cemetery. In the background is P.S. No. 95, at the N.E. corner of Neck Road and Van Sicklen Street.
February 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4)
The same, showing a northwest view. The house at the extreme right is No. 373 Van Sicklen Street.
April 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

name: Brooklyn: Van Sicklen St. - Village Rd. N.
$.data.text:
(1)
Van Sicklen Street, at the S.E. corner of Village Road North, showing the home of the Van Sicklen's, which was erected in 1776, by John who deeded the property to his son Court. Subsequent members to hold it were, J.C. 1860, C.I. 1873, and J.L. Van Sicklen in 1890. Mrs. Margaret Van Sicklen Goodchild who was residing in California, sold it in September 1925 to a builder. It was razed in 1929.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, at a later date.
April 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(3)
The same, a closer view.
April 1923.

$.data.text:
Van Sinderen Ave., at the S.W. corner of Fulton Street, showing the Manhattan Hotel. Also seen is the Fulton Street Elevated Line of the B.1.T. In 1873 this hotel known as the Metropolitan, was owned by Robert Smith. It stood on the Brooklyn town line. This hotel was demolished in 1924, and a 2-story building was erected by the Western Electric Co.
1922.

name: Brooklyn: Village Rd. N. - McDonald Ave.
$.data.text:
(1) Village Road North, north side, between McDonald Ave., and Village Road East, showing the Williamson house which was erected in 1780. This house is 50 feet distant from the former house which was erected in 1665. This land upon which the house is situated, is said to have been a grant made by Queen Ann to this family in 1665. This house was demolished in 1929.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, a view west. The Culver Elevated Line of the B.M.T. is seen in the background on McDonald Ave.
1922.

1922.

name: Brooklyn: Wyona St. - Fulton St.
$.data.text:
Wyona Ave., east side, between Fulton Street and Atlantic Ave., showing the Trinity Church (P.E.). Lyman Cobb, shortly after settling in East New York in 1850, organized the Episcopal Society, which in 1854 purchased this edifice from the Congregation of the Reformed Church. This structure built for church services in 1840, was no longer used as one in 1916. The real estate maps of 1929 show a 4-story brick building on the site.

About 1880.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
